            <td>Familiar Interface</td>
            <td>Free / $3/mo</td>
            <td>3.8/5</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="best-overall">Best Overall: Bitwarden</h2>
      <p>Bitwarden won because it is the only password manager that delivers a genuinely complete free tier with no time limits, no device restrictions, and no nag screens. Unlimited passwords on unlimited devices, cross-platform sync, and a browser extension that autofills as well as paid competitors — all for $0. For most individual users, Bitwarden free is all you will ever need.</p>
      <p>The open-source architecture is what sets Bitwarden apart from every closed-source competitor. The code is publicly audited by third-party security firms, and anyone can inspect the encryption implementation. This matters because password managers hold the keys to your digital life, and trust based on a company's word is weaker than trust based on verifiable code. Bitwarden uses AES-256 bit encryption with PBKDF2 key derivation, the same standards used by banks and governments.</p>
      <p>The trade-off is the interface. Bitwarden's apps are functional but less polished than 1Password's, with more manual clicking required for some workflows. The autofill is reliable but occasionally requires a second attempt on unusual login forms. For users who prioritize security and free access over a slick UI, these are minor complaints. The $10 per year premium tier adds 2FA token storage, encrypted file attachments, and priority support — still cheaper than any competitor's paid plan.</p>

      <div class="product-box">
        <h2>Bitwarden</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Completely free tier</strong> — unlimited passwords on unlimited devices, no time limit</li>
          <li><strong>Open source and audited</strong> — code is publicly reviewed by security experts</li>
          <li><strong>Cross-platform</strong> — every browser, desktop OS, and mobile platform</li>
          <li><strong>AES-256 encryption</strong> — zero-knowledge architecture, master password never leaves your device</li>
          <li><strong>Premium at $10/year</strong> — adds 2FA tokens, file storage, and priority support</li>
        </ul>
        <a href="https://bitwarden.com" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow sponsored">Get Bitwarden Free</a>
      </div>

      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Premium: 1Password</h2>
      <p>1Password is the choice if you are willing to pay for the best user experience and have no history of security breaches. At $2.99 per month, it costs more than Bitwarden's free tier but delivers a noticeably more polished app. The autofill is the most reliable in this comparison across desktop and mobile, and the Watchtower feature alerts you when a stored password appears in known data breaches.</p>
      <p>The standout feature is Travel Mode, which temporarily removes sensitive vaults from your device when crossing borders and restores them when you arrive. For anyone who travels internationally for work, this is a genuine security feature that no competitor matches. The family plan at $4.99 per month covers up to five people with shared vaults for things like streaming services and household accounts.</p>
      <p>The trade-off is price and the lack of a free tier. 1Password offers only a 14-day trial, after which you pay. For users who want the smoothest experience and are happy to pay for it, 1Password is worth the money. For everyone else, Bitwarden's free tier covers the same core functionality without the cost.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>The first decision is whether you need a free or paid password manager. For most individuals, Bitwarden's free tier is complete — unlimited passwords, unlimited devices, cross-platform sync. You only need to pay if you want built-in 2FA token storage (which you can otherwise get from a free authenticator app) or encrypted file attachments. Families should consider 1Password's family plan or Bitwarden's $40 per year premium for family sharing.</p>
      <p>Security architecture matters more than marketing claims. Look for zero-knowledge encryption, meaning the company cannot decrypt your vault even if compelled by law enforcement. Open-source code that is independently audited is a strong signal of security, because the implementation can be verified. Avoid managers with a history of breaches that exposed customer data, even if the encrypted passwords themselves held — the breach handling reveals the company's security culture.</p>
      <p>Common mistakes to avoid: do not use your browser's built-in password manager as your only tool — they lack cross-browser sync and advanced features like breach alerts. Do not reuse your master password anywhere else; if that one password leaks, your entire vault is exposed. Avoid managers that do not support two-factor authentication on the master login. And never store your master password in a notes app or text file — write it on paper and store it somewhere secure.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">testing methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Are password managers really safe?</summary>
          <p>Yes. Reputable password managers like Bitwarden and 1Password use zero-knowledge encryption, meaning even the company cannot access your passwords. Your master password never leaves your device in unencrypted form. The bigger security risk is reusing passwords across sites, which a password manager eliminates. Using a password manager is dramatically safer than the alternative of reusing or weak passwords.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Can I use Bitwarden for free forever?</summary>
          <p>Yes. Bitwarden's personal free tier includes unlimited passwords on unlimited devices, with no time limit and no credit card required. The paid tier at $10 per year adds 2FA tokens, encrypted file storage, and priority support, but the free tier is fully usable for most individuals indefinitely. There is no downgrade pressure or nagging upgrade prompts.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What happened to LastPass?</summary>
          <p>LastPass suffered a major data breach in late 2022 that exposed customer vault metadata and encrypted password blobs. While the encrypted passwords themselves were not directly cracked, the breach and LastPass's slow, incomplete disclosure led many security professionals to recommend switching to Bitwarden or 1Password. LastPass remains functional, but its security track record makes it harder to recommend over alternatives.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

